Content: Fill in the bubbles before TWO phrases Ovid uses in Passage 1 to show that Pyramus and Thisbe experience a shared love.

:box:	“ :MC-A: A thing which they could not forbid, :MC-B: they were both inflamed, with minds equally captivated. :MC-C: There is no one acquainted with it; :MC-D: by nods and signs, they hold converse. :MC-E: And the more the fire is smothered, :MC-F: the more, when so smothered, does it burn. :MC-G: The party-wall, common to the two houses, :MC-H: was cleft by a small chink, which it had got formerly, when it was built. :MC-I: This defect, remarked by no one for so many ages, :MC-J: you lovers (what does not love perceive?) first found one, :MC-K: and you made it a passage for your voices, :MC-L: and the accents of love used to pass through it in safety, with the gentlest murmur. :MC-M: Oftentimes, after they had taken their stations, Thisbe on one side, and Pyramus on the other, :MC-N: and the breath of their mouths had been mutually caught by turns, . . .” (paragraph 1)

Key.Rationale: The descriptions of Thisbe’s and Pyramus’s behavior and state of mind reveal how they experience the same love for one another.
The phrase shows that both Thisbe and Pyramus share their affection for one another.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Based on Pyramus and Thisbe’s situation, what is a theme of Passage 1?

B.Choice: True love finds ways to overcome any obstacle.

Key.Rationale: Despite the obstacle of the wall, the love of Pyramus and Thisbe remains strong.

C.Choice: The smallest defect can cause love to deteriorate.

D.Choice: Family disapproval can lead to desperate measures.

Content: Which detail from Passage 1 helps develop the theme in Part A?

Key.Rationale: Pyramus and Thisbe use a defect in the wall (which otherwise is an obstacle) in order to communicate, which they would not otherwise be able to do.

Content: At the end of Passage 1, why does Ovid use the word “envious” to describe the wall?

A.Choice: It is immune ot the pain that Pyramus and Thisbe experience.

B.Choice: It has a flaw that Pyramus and Thisbe associate with their love.

C.Choice: It hears theo pinions Pyramus and Thisbe have about each other.

D.Choice: It experiences the physical contact that Pyramus and Thisbe desire.

Key.Rationale: The use of the word “envious” refers to the idea that the wall is keeping Pyramus and Thisbe physically apart.

Content: In Passage 2, how do sections 6–10 increase the tension of the passage as a whole?

A.Choice: They show that Romeo is questioning his identity.

B.Choice: They show that Juliet misinterprets Romeo's motives.

C.Choice: They raise the possibility that Juliet may reject Romeo.

D.Choice: They emphasize the danger that Romeo faces if caught.

Key.Rationale: The details about Juliet’s kinsmen and the violence they would perhaps inflict on Romeo pervade the rest of the passage, giving an underlying tension to the exchanges that follow.

Content: Romeo and Juliet retells the Pyramus and Thisbe myth in the form of a play. In the excerpt provided in Passage 2, what does the play format help Shakespeare to emphasize about his characters? Select TWO options.

Key.Rationale: Although Ovid only says that Pyramus’s and Thisbe’s fathers forbid their marriage, Shakespeare dramatizes the family disapproval by suggesting that they may kill Romeo if they find him there.
While Passage 1 presents the characters as having nearly identical sentiments, Romeo and Juliet’s exchanges are full of questions and mixed emotions.

D.Choice: the way society views their relationship

E.Choice: the reasons for their families' disapproval

F.Choice: the reasons they are drawn to each other

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Which quotation from Passage 2 summarizes a theme of both passages?

A.Choice: “The orchard walls are high and hard to climb; ...” (section 6)

B.Choice: “For stony limits cannot hold love out: ...” (section 7)

Key.Rationale: This quote reveals the theme in both passages that love can overcome obstacles.

C.Choice: “Thou knowest the mask of night is on my face; ...” (section 14)

D.Choice: “I have no joy of this contract to-night; ...” (section 20)

Content: How does Shakespeare dramatize this theme differently than Ovid does in Passage 1?

A.Choice: by placing the characters in a definite setting

B.Choice: by increasing the conflict between the characters

C.Choice: by changing the type of obstacle the characters face

Key.Rationale: Shakespeare removes the physical barrier that Ovid leaves between his characters and replaces it with the cover of darkness, thus opening up more dramatic possibilities in the scene.

D.Choice: by allowing the characters to engage in conversation

Content: Which phrase supports Mott’s position that women’s rights are “of greater importance to the well-being of society at large?”

Key.Rationale: Mott’s emphasis on the “higher nature” in written works shows her belief that forms of popular entertainment should have a moral component.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What central idea about language does Mott express in Passage 1?

A.Choice: Flattering words have failed to satisfy women's need for equality.

B.Choice: Attempts should be made to educate those who use vulgar speech.

C.Choice: Women must learn how to speak well before they can rise in society.

D.Choice: Artistic words can conceal ideas that limit the progress of equal rights.

Key.Rationale: Mott objects to the lecture she attends because its apparent eloquence conceals ideas she sees as damaging to women’s progress.

Content: What does Mott cite in paragraphs 3 and 4 as evidence that this situation is changing?

Key.Rationale: In paragraph 4, Mott makes a point that the sentimental novels previously marketed to women are giving way to more substantial fare.

Content: Read the excerpt from Passage 1.
:box:“There is nothing of greater importance to the well-being of society at large—of man as well as woman—than the true and proper position of woman.” (paragraph 1)
After stating this central claim, how does Mott structure the rest of the passage?

A.Choice: She criticizes the immaturity of the young and then pleads for better education.

B.Choice: She names obstacles to progress and then cites positive signs of improvement.

Key.Rationale: Mott names the lecture she attends as an example of how much there still is to combat but proceeds to discuss a number of ways in which the women’s movement has made positive strides.

C.Choice: She describes the role of men and then shows how they can help the movement.

D.Choice: She stresses the importance of communication and then describes what it can accomplish.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Read this excerpt from Passage 2.

:box:But neither the advice to go to Paris nor the suggestion of disguise tempted me for a moment. It was to my mind a moral crusade on which I had entered, a course of justice and common sense, and it must be pursued in the light of day, and with p͟u͟b͟l͟i͟c͟ ͟s͟a͟n͟c͟t͟i͟o͟n, in order to accomplish its end. (paragraph 11)
Based on the phrase p͟u͟b͟l͟i͟c͟ ͟s͟a͟n͟c͟t͟i͟o͟n, in what way was Blackwell determined to accomplish her goals?

Key.Rationale: The phrase and subsequent surrounding text indicate that Blackwell wishes to accomplish her goals without having to disguise herself or study elsewhere. She wants the public to know what she intends to accomplish.

Content: Which phrase from the excerpt provides a clue to the meaning of the phrase p͟u͟b͟l͟i͟c͟ ͟s͟a͟n͟c͟t͟i͟o͟n?

Key.Rationale: The phrase “in the light of day” indicates that Blackwell wishes to accomplish her goals with everyone knowing about it.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What is Blackwell’s purpose for describing her experiences in Passage 2?

A.Choice: to show how she handled the obstacles in the way of her goals

Key.Rationale: Blackwell mentions that she applied to many medical colleges without gaining entry, but that did not deter her from accomplishing her goal of becoming a doctor.

B.Choice: to criticize the physicians who discouraged her interest in medicine

C.Choice: to illustrate how effective women could be in traditional male roles

D.Choice: to argue that medicine would benefit if more women were involved

Content: Which phrase does Blackwell use to help emphasize this purpose?

Key.Rationale: This phrase describes how Blackwell approached the obstacles she faced gaining entry into a medical college.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
How are Mott’s and Blackwell’s perspectives similar?

A.Choice: Both view women's rights as an ethical issue.

Key.Rationale: Mott’s repeated appeals for achieving an “elevated position” for women and Blackwell’s pronouncement that she is on a “moral crusade” support this interpretation.

B.Choice: Both think intellect can conceal destructive ideas.

C.Choice: Both recognize positive signs in women's progress.

D.Choice: Both emphasize the importance of self-confidence.

Content: Select TWO quotations that support the answer in Part A.

A.Choice: “... a more elevated position than that which custom for ages has allotted to her.” (paragraph 2)

Key.Rationale: The use of the phrase “elevated position” indicates that Mott views women’s rights as an ethical issue.

B.Choice: “I regretted the more that these sentiments should be presented with such intellectual vigor. . . .” (paragraph 2)

C.Choice: “A new generation of women is now upon the stage, improving the increased opportunities. . . .” (paragraph 4)

D.Choice: “... the idea was a good one, but that it was impossible to accomplish it.” (paragraph 6)

E.Choice: “... rather an encouragement than otherwise to a young and active person. . . .” (paragraph 7)

F.Choice: “It was to my mind a moral crusade on which I had entered, a course of justice and common sense, . . .” (paragraph 11)

Key.Rationale: The use of the phrase “moral crusade” indicates that Blackwell views women’s rights as an ethical issue.

Content: Both Elizabeth Blackwell in Passage 2 and Mary Ellen Avery in Passage 3 emphasize their efforts to be admitted to medical school. Fill in the bubbles to show which details match each passage.

Key.Rationale: In Passage 3, Dr. Avery describes how Emily Bacon reached out to her to serve as a great influence and inspiration in her life to become a doctor.
Both Passages 2 and 3 describe the lack of schools that were willing to admit women who wanted to enter the medical field.
Paragraph 6 describes the discouragement Blackwell received from people as she expressed her desire to enter the medical field.

Content: Choose the correct phrase to complete the underlined part of the first paragraph.

A.Choice: Kennedy charms the public with his natural gift of clear communication.

B.Choice: Kennedy charmed the public with his natural gift of clear communication.

Key.Rationale: This option uses parallel structure throughout.

C.Choice: Kennedy will charm the public with his natural gift of clear communication.

Content: Choose the correct spelling to replace the first underlined part of the second paragraph.

Key.Rationale: This is the correct spelling of the word “resonate.”

Content: Choose the correct punctuation to replace the second underlined part of the second paragraph.

Key.Rationale: A semicolon is the correct choice because it separates two independent, but related, ideas.

Key.Rationale: The adjectival phrase is included to emphasize the benefits of storytelling in speeches.
